I want to build project using OxyJen and Springboot to demonstrate that i am a beast at backend
The project: a mini deterministic compliance engine
This maps directly onto what SAMMY does, and it's a natural extension of OxyJen rather than a new thing to learn.
Concept: A backend service that takes a structured fact set (JSON) + a jurisdiction, runs it through a graph of rule-nodes, and returns a verdict with a full provenance trail — which rules fired, in what order, citing which regulation, and why. This is literally "statutes → deterministic engine → verdict with provenance," just scoped small.
How to build it with what you already have:

OxyJen provides the graph engine: each compliance rule becomes a NodePlugin (e.g., KYCThresholdNode, DataRetentionNode). Use RouterNode/BranchNode for conditional logic ("if transaction > $10,000, evaluate AML node"), MergeNode to combine multiple rule outcomes into one verdict.
NodeContext becomes your provenance trail — every node writes its decision + citation into context as it fires, so the final output isn't just "PASS/FAIL" but a structured audit log.
Spring Boot wraps this as a REST API: POST /evaluate → takes facts JSON → returns { verdict, provenance: [{rule, citation, result}], latencyMs }.
Bonus that directly speaks their language: log and expose the actual evaluation latency in the response. Even if you're not hitting their 12ms claim, showing you're measuring and thinking about latency as a first-class concern signals you understood their pitch, not just their tech stack.

Keep the rule set tiny and toy — 4-5 rules (say, basic KYC/AML-style checks) is plenty. The point isn't legal accuracy, it's proving the architecture: deterministic, traceable, same input → same output, every time. This is the mini project you can enhance it with what this domain needs